                <head>106. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On May 31, 1967, from 1:15 to 2:30 p.m., President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1"
                        >Johnson</persName> held a luncheon meeting with Secretaries <persName
                        corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1"
                        >McNamara</persName>, Vice President <persName corresp="#p_HHH1"
                        >Humphrey</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_CG1">George
                    Christian</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">Walt Rostow</persName>.
                    The latter’s agenda for the meeting indicates that next steps in the Near East
                    crisis headed the agenda, with the focus on the <persName corresp="#p_RD1"
                        >Rusk</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>
                    recommendations in <ref target="#d103">Document 103</ref>. A briefing memorandum
                    prepared for Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> similarly
                    indicates that the <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>-<persName
                        corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> recommendations would be discussed
                    and lists three additional points under the topic Middle East Crisis. The first
                    item, “Use of U–2,” is not further explained. An attached “G memo” (presumably a
                    memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_KFD1">Kohler</persName>) is not attached
                    to the briefing memorandum. The second item states that the President wanted
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> or <persName corresp="#p_REV1"
                        >Eugene Rostow</persName> to call in <persName corresp="#p_HA1"
                        >Harman</persName> and “indicate to him formally where the <persName
                        corresp="#p_EL1">Eshkol</persName> letter exceeded the statement of our
                    commitment.” The third item states that <persName corresp="#p_SJJ1"
                        >Sisco</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_BLD1">Battle</persName>, and
                        <persName corresp="#p_MLC1">Meeker</persName> were forming a Task Force to
                    consider urgently possible solutions other than the US/<gloss target="#t_UK1"
                        >UK</gloss> Maritime Plan, and that the President had told <persName
                        corresp="#p_RWW1">Walt Rostow</persName> that morning that he “wanted urgent
                    work done on this.” (National Archives and Records Administration, <gloss
                        target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, President’s Luncheon Memoranda: Lot 70 D
                    164)</p>
